        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real community management examples</h2>
        <p>Two examples showing how the discipline moves real numbers.</p>

        <h3>1. Local gym on Instagram</h3>
        <p>A city-based gym committed to replying to every Instagram comment within 30 minutes and featuring one member per week in Stories. Six months in: engagement rate up 200%, new-member referrals up 40%. The gym did not increase ad spend, add classes, or hire trainers — the entire lift came from consistent two-way engagement with an audience that already existed.</p>

        <h3>2. B2B SaaS Slack community</h3>
        <p>A project-management SaaS opened a Slack community for power users. They ran weekly async Q&A, invited product managers into channels, and highlighted user wins in a monthly digest. Members of the community showed <strong>18% lower churn</strong> than non-members over 12 months, and generated most of the qualitative input that fed the next product roadmap. The Slack cost a few hours per week to moderate and paid back in retention alone.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Community management vs social media marketing — clarify the split</h2>
        <p>Every team eventually asks whether these should be one role or two. The right answer depends on scale.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Community management owns</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Replies, DMs, comment moderation</li>
              <li>Sentiment tracking and escalations</li>
              <li>Community members, member spotlights, VIPs</li>
              <li>Owned spaces (Slack, Discord, forums)</li>
              <li>Response-time SLAs</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Social media marketing owns</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Content calendar and post publishing</li>
              <li>Creative assets (photo, video, graphics)</li>
              <li>Paid boosts and influencer collaborations</li>
              <li>Follower growth and reach metrics</li>
              <li>Campaign planning and hashtag strategy</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 community management best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Set response-time SLAs and track them weekly.</strong> Under 1 hour for complaints, under 4 hours for questions, same-day for DMs.</li>
          <li><strong>Write a voice guide before you scale headcount.</strong> One page. Tone words, banned phrases, escalation triggers, humor level.</li>
          <li><strong>Centralize monitoring in one tool.</strong> Sprout Social, Buffer, or Statusbrew for cross-platform inboxes; native tools for single-platform teams.</li>
          <li><strong>Balance reactive with proactive.</strong> Every week: one prompt, one member spotlight, one behind-the-scenes moment.</li>
          <li><strong>Route escalations, do not ignore them.</strong> Product bugs to engineering, PR-level complaints to comms, sales-ready signals to revenue.</li>
          <li><strong>Track sentiment, not just volume.</strong> A 20% drop in positive sentiment is the earliest signal that a product change, price change, or campaign has landed badly.</li>
          <li><strong>Report to the exec team monthly.</strong> Community moves are hard to feel from the outside — a monthly one-pager keeps the discipline funded.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common mistake — copy-paste replies</div>
          <p>Automation and canned responses look efficient until members recognize them. The moment a community realizes replies are templated, engagement collapses. Use snippets for structure, not verbatim replies. Even a two-sentence customized response outperforms a polished template.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common community management mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Ignoring negative comments.</strong> Silence reads as guilt. Reply publicly, then move to DM.</li>
          <li><strong>Broadcasting in community spaces.</strong> Slack and Discord die the moment the brand starts posting like it is a marketing channel.</li>
          <li><strong>Over-moderating.</strong> Removing dissent kills trust faster than any negative comment.</li>
          <li><strong>Rotating community managers.</strong> Community trust is earned by consistent voices. Constant CM turnover restarts the trust clock.</li>
          <li><strong>Metrics obsession.</strong> Chasing engagement rate can produce bait content that undermines the real relationship.</li>
          <li><strong>No response-time tracking.</strong> Without a target, response times drift and nobody notices until it hits Trustpilot.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="how-thestacc-helps">How theStacc helps with community management</h2>
        <p>Community-management output only compounds if the content it engages with is worth engaging with. theStacc ships the top-of-funnel content — articles, guides, and comparison pages — that gives your community something meaningful to share, defend, and discuss. Community managers get a steady supply of quality material to point audiences at, and the SEO-driven traffic from that content routes new prospects into the community-managed spaces where retention actually happens.</p>

